Section1.Para:
The influence of the surface microstructure of aqua blasted and laser engraved conditions on the corrosion resistance was investigated using atmospheric corrosion tests in a humidity cabinet. The specimens were exposed at 50 °C and 30 % relative humidity for 370 days. MgCl2 droplets with a volume of 2.5 µl were applied onto the surfaces using an eppendorf pipette, leading to an MgCl2 deposition density of ~ 38, 386 and 772 µg/cm2. Key objective of the atmospheric corrosion tests was to identify the most likely surface condition to initiate localised corrosion, and specimens were therefore regularly removed from the chamber for inspection using optical microcopy. An image segmentation routine based on ImageJ (
                  http://imagej.nih.gov/ij/

                ), Adobe Photoshop was used to obtain and quantify changes of the corroded area over time. The corroded area is defined as the area fraction (%) covered by visible corrosion products within the droplet area (total area). The area of the corrosion product development was assessed to find a correlation between surface observation and the depth of attack.
